# Student Activity Sheet
## Publishing to the Internet with GitHub Pages

**Your goal today:** Build a page about something you love and publish it on the
internet with a real URL you can share with anyone.


## What are we making?

A **page about a topic you choose**: a fan page, a top-5 list, a tribute,
anything.

Some ideas:
- Your football club
- A game you're into
- Your favorite artist or playlist
- A show, film, or anime you love
- Literally anything you care about

**My topic:** `______________________________`


## One thing before we start

Your page will be **public**. Anyone with the link can see it.

A good rule: **"Would I be okay if a stranger, a teacher, or my parents saw
this?"**

Safe to publish: nicknames, interests, fan content, quotes  
Think twice: your full real name, school name, city, photos of yourself


## The tools we'll use

Everything you need, nothing to install:

| Tool                  | What it does                    | Why we use it                                  |
| --------------------- | ------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------- |
| **GitHub**            | Stores your files online        | Free, trusted, used by professionals worldwide |
| **GitHub Pages**      | Turns your files into a website | No cost, no server needed                      |
| **GitHub Web Editor** | Edit files in the browser       | No installs required, works on any computer    |


## Your Checklist

### ☐ Step 1 — Create your GitHub account

1. Go to **[github.com](https://github.com)** and click **Sign up**
2. Enter your email, create a password, and choose a username

    > 💡 You don't have to use your real name. Something like `falacoelho` or
    > `guitarreiro22` works great.  
    > Letters, numbers, and underscores only. No space.

3. Complete the verification steps

**My username:** `______________________________`


### ☐ Step 2 — Create your repository

1. Click the **+** icon (top-right) → **New repository**
2. Name it exactly:

    ```
    yourusername.github.io
    ```

    *(Replace `yourusername` with your actual GitHub username. Must match exactly)*

3. Set to **Public**
4. Check **"Add a README file"**
5. Click **Create repository**

### ☐ Step 3 — Create your HTML file

1. Inside your repository, click **Add file → Create new file**
2. Name it exactly: `index.html`
3. Copy and paste the template below
4. Replace all the `[placeholder]` text with your own content
5. Click **Commit changes**, then confirm


## Your starter template

You can copy the source code from here: https://chrs.to/SiIF1.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="pt-BR">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Minha Página</title>
</head>
<body>
  <h1 style="color: #e63946;">[NOME DO SEU TEMA]</h1>
  <p>[Apresentação — uma ou duas frases]</p>

  <h2>Top 3</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>[Item 1]</li>
    <li>[Item 2]</li>
    <li>[Item 3]</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Feito por: [seu apelido]</p>
</body>
</html>
```

> 💡 Want a different color? Go to **[coolors.co](https://coolors.co)**, pick
> one, and replace `#e63946` with your hex code.


### ☐ Step 4 — Enable GitHub Pages

1. Click **Settings** in the top menu of your repository
2. In the left sidebar, click **Pages**
3. Under **Source**, select **Deploy from a branch**
4. Branch: **main** | Folder: **/ (root)**
5. Click **Save**
6. Wait 1–2 minutes, then refresh. Your URL appears! 🎉

**My URL:** `https://______________________________`


### ☐ Step 5 — Make it yours

Go back to your `index.html` and keep editing:

- [ ] Replace every `[placeholder]` with real content
- [ ] Change the color to something you like
- [ ] Add more `<h2>` sections if you want more content
- [ ] Delete sections you don't need

Note: Every time you click **Commit changes**, your site updates in about 1
minute.


### ☐ Step 6 — Share it

1. Open your URL in a new tab
2. Test it on your phone
3. Share the link with a classmate — open each other's pages


## Done!

You just learned:
- What a **repository** is
- What **HTML** does
- How **GitHub Pages** turns a file into a website
- That publishing to the internet is something anyone can do

## Homework (optional but fun)

Open any AI assistant (ChatGPT, Claude, etc.), paste your HTML, and say:

> *"Make this page look better."*

Copy the result back into your `index.html`, commit, and see what changed.

